Now I have the full server picture. Let me confirm my findings and look at a few more.

**Confirmed Finding: `resolveTemporarySubscriptions` increments quota and the aggregator only persists when `changed`.** 

Looking at the resolver: `resolverQuotaUsed += 1` happens per temp subscription before the call. If the resolution succeeds and produces a `realId`, `changed = true`. But if the API returns no items (e.g., channel doesn't exist) or fails, `changed` stays false for that sub, but quota was incremented. Then in the aggregator:

```js
resolverQuotaUsed = resolveResult.resolverQuotaUsed;
parsedData.settings.quotaUsed = resolverQuotaUsed;
if (resolveResult.changed) {
    parsedData.subscriptions = resolveResult.subscriptions;
    await appStore.writeData(parsedData);
}
```

So if no sub changed (all already resolved or all failed), `writeData` is NOT called, so `quotaUsed` is not persisted. Next aggregation reads the old (lower) `quotaUsed`, so the cap can be exceeded. This is a real bug but MED confidence on severity (only matters when YOUTUBE_API_KEY is set and there are unresolved handles that fail to resolve). Actually it also matters when the resolver succeeds: if it resolves and changes subs, quota IS persisted. So the gap is only on the "no-change" path. Still a correctness gap. Confidence MED.

